In article <strnlghtCJ694w.BIF@netcom.com> strnlght@netcom.com (David 
Sternlight) writes: 

>Let me give you a simple example. Some years ago there was a lot of concern
>about accidental or malicious launch of nuclear weapons. I worked in the
>private sector for a distinguished former senior sub-cabinet Defense
>official (I'm being a bit vague to protect his identity) who had been
>involved in the system. He told me (this was many years ago) that the
>problem the government was worried about was that they couldn't launch when
>they were supposed to, not that they'd launch when they weren't. He was
>making a technical statement about the built-in safeguards.

The fact that a system won't work is no assurance that it will fail safe.

The proof of this follows directly from Murphy's law.

